Dear Mariyaiya,

Thank you for this feedback. I have gone through it carefully, and I 
want to respond in full — both to acknowledge what you have accomplished 
and *to give the entire team the correct framework for using these two 
tools in SPINRISE.
*
*Before anything else:* completing the Purchase Requisition form 
end-to-end using Claude Code in one to two days, as a first attempt, on 
one of the most technically complex forms in the entire Kalsofte ERP — a 
form with 9,108 lines of VB6 code, 24 database tables, three stored 
procedures, 25 error messages, and a 10-state approval lifecycle — is a 
significant achievement. This is the first concrete proof that the 
SPINRISE migration approach is technically viable at the scale we are 
targeting. *Well done.*

*Your technical observations are accurate. Let me validate and extend 
them for the team.*

*On Claude AI*

Your description is correct.*Claude AI,* accessed through the browser, 
is a code and documentation generator. It produces complete, 
well-structured output from a single prompt, but it has no access to the 
file system, cannot create project folders, cannot install packages, and 
cannot run or test the code it generates. Every block of code it 
produces must be manually extracted, placed in the right file, connected 
to the right modules, and tested by the developer. For a single-screen 
prototype this is manageable. For 98 forms across the PO module 
alone,*it is not a scalable approach for code generation.
*
However — and *this is important for the whole team to understand *— 
Claude AI is not the wrong tool. It is the right tool for the wrong 
stage if used for code generation. Claude AI is the correct tool for 
Stage 0 and FSD documentation. It reads VB6 code and produces 
plain-English specifications faster and more thoroughly than any 
developer can write them manually. The entire FSD process we have built 
— Stage 0, the 14-section template, the six follow-up prompts, the IST 
structured questionnaire — is designed around Claude AI. That is where 
it belongs.


*On Claude Code*

Your description is also correct.*Claude Code is an agentic developer 
running inside VS Code*. It has direct access to the project file 
system. It creates files, folders, and scaffolds. It installs packages, 
runs commands, reads compile errors, and corrects them without being 
asked. It builds front-end and back-end together in the same session. 
*The developer's role changes from manual code assembler to prompt 
director and quality reviewer. *This is the right tool for Stage 1 — 
code generation from an approved FSD.

Your observation that it requires incremental prompting throughout is an 
important nuance for the team to understand.*Claude Code is not a 
one-prompt solution.* *It works in phases:* project scaffold, API 
service layer, React components, validation logic, error handling, 
testing. *The developer must guide each phase with precise prompts. *The 
quality of the prompting directly determines the quality and speed of 
the output. This is a skill that must be built deliberately.

*The sequence that must never be violated*

*For the full team, I want to state the SPINRISE tool sequence as a 
rule, not a guideline:*

   Stage 0 and FSD documentation  →  Claude AI (browser)
   FSD review chain  →  Four human review levels, CEO approval
   Code generation  →  Claude Code (VS Code), using ONLY the 
CEO-approved FSD as input
   IST validation  →  Module Sr IST Member tests Claude Code output 
against VB6 original

This sequence exists for one reason. Claude Code will implement exactly 
what it is told. If it is given the approved FSD — which correctly marks 
the three Critical defects in the PR form as defects to be corrected, 
not replicated — it will build the corrected version. If it is instead 
given the raw VB6 code, it will replicate the application-terminating 
End statement, the hardcoded customer ID logic, the SQL injection 
patterns, and the Oracle SQL branches directly into the new SPINRISE 
screen. *The FSD is the quality filter between the legacy defects and 
the new platform*. Bypassing it bypasses that filter entirely.

*No developer may use Claude Code on any SPINRISE module form until that 
form has a CEO-approved FSD.* Exploratory familiarisation on 
non-production practice forms this week is encouraged. *Production 
SPINRISE forms: approved FSD first, then Claude Code.*

*A question that must be answered before the PR form is considered complete
*
Mariyaiya, I need to understand the basis on which you used Claude Code 
for the PR form. Were you working from the approved FSD — which does not 
yet exist for this form, as Muthuvel's IST review is still pending — or 
were you working from your own domain knowledge and the VB6 code? I ask 
this not to diminish the work but because the answer determines the 
validation required. If the Claude Code output was generated from the 
VB6 code directly, the three Critical defects may exist in the generated 
screen and must be found and corrected before the output can be 
accepted. Muthuvel's IST validation of the Claude Code output against 
the VB6 original is mandatory regardless of the input source. A 
generated screen is not a validated screen.

*On project structure — a prerequisite before the team scales Claude Code*

Before any developer other than Mariyaiya begins Claude Code work on 
SPINRISE module forms, the following must be in place:

*TL-Dev Sasi must define and lock the SPINRISE project structure *— 
folder conventions, naming standards, API response format, React 
component patterns, error handling patterns, and database connection 
approach. Claude Code creates files and folders. If each developer 
starts independently without a locked structure, the codebase will be 
inconsistent across modules and impossible to maintain. *The project 
scaffold is TL-Dev's responsibility and it must be done before the team 
scales.*

This is the action I am asking TL-Dev Sasi to prioritise this week 
alongside Stage 0 readiness for M02.

*For the team — five instructions effective immediately*

1.  The tool sequence is mandatory. Claude AI for FSD documentation. 
Claude Code for code generation from an approved FSD. In that order. No 
exceptions.

2. *Mariyaiya to present a Claude Code demonstration to the full team 
this Saturday, 11 April morning session.* Show the prompting sequence, 
the project structure created, and the output produced for the PR form. 
PM Saravanan to add this to Saturday's agenda. This is the most valuable 
knowledge transfer we can do this week.

3.  Mariyaiya to document the Claude Code prompting sequence used for 
the PR form as a written note — the phases, the key prompts, the 
corrections made, the time taken per phase. This becomes the first entry 
in the SPINRISE Developer Reference for Claude Code usage. *Share with 
the team before Saturday.*

4. *TL-Dev Sasi to define and share the SPINRISE project structure this 
week.* All developers to align to this structure before beginning any 
Claude Code work on module forms.

5. *All developers to begin Claude Code familiarisation this week on 
non-production exploratory forms. *Build the prompting skill before the 
approved FSDs arrive. When the first approved FSD is ready, you should 
be able to use Claude Code fluently on day one.
*
The bigger picture*

*Mariyaiya's result *— one to two days for a complete PR form cycle 
using Claude Code — gives us our first real productivity benchmark for 
the SPINRISE migration. Across 98 items in the PO module, even at a 
conservative average of one and a half days per transaction form, the 
code generation phase becomes a weeks-long exercise rather than a 
months-long one. *The constraint is no longer development speed. The 
constraint is the quality and completeness of the approved FSDs that 
feed Claude Code.*

This is why the Stage 0 and FSD documentation work we are doing right 
now is not preliminary work. It is the main work. It is what determines 
how fast and how accurately Claude Code can build SPINRISE. Every week 
we invest in getting the FSDs right is a week we save in rework after 
code generation.

*The tools are working. The process is sound. The team is moving.*

With confidence in what this team is building,
T Mani

cc: TL-Dev Sasi, PM Saravanan, Muthuvel, Annamalai, Sathiskumar, 
Abinandan, Hariharan, TL-IST Palanivel, Full SPINRISE Team

